<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6637&amp;p=64779#p64779</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6637&amp;p=64779#p64779"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Real NES like testing on an Emulator?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6637&amp;p=64779#p64779"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">NESICIDE wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">A "tintpoint" would be like a breakpoint, but instead of stopping execution, it would set the tint bits when it triggers.<br /></div><br />Which, I *think*, is equivalent in most respects to the run-time interface via the IDE, which allows you to set a marked region of code -- aka "tintpoint" -- the only difference being the color used to represent the change of state.</div><br />Exactly, except the parallel with breakpoints might help people understand it better, and it would also allow setting color on events other than execution at a particular address. Breakpoint, tintpoint, soundpoint, logpoint, savepoint, scriptpoint, cedarpoint, it's just an idea for making your debugger engine more <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonality#Computer_science" class="postlink">orthogonal</a>. It separates the "when" (e.g. opcode fetch, read address, write address, write particular data at address) from the "what" (stop execution, set the color, play a sound, write the registers and a bit of text, save a state for later analysis, run a Lua script, ride a roller coaster).<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Sat Jul 24, 2010 1:00 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
