<div class="quotetitle">tepples wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br /><div class="quotetitle">NESICIDE wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">The difference here is that in that method the Execution Visualizer would show what your code is doing because your code is doing it [ie. turning on/off the tint bits].  In my example though the Execution Visualizer shows what your code is doing because you asked the IDE to show it to you<br /></div><br />Which leads to a nice way to unify the two using the breakpoint system. A "tintpoint" would be like a breakpoint, but instead of stopping execution, it would set the tint bits when it triggers.</div><br /><br />Which, I *think*, is equivalent in most respects to the run-time interface via the IDE, which allows you to set a marked region of code -- aka "tintpoint" -- the only difference being the color used to represent the change of state.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=3705">cpow</a> — Sat Jul 24, 2010 12:34 pm</p><hr />
